@inproceedings{packet-alter,
	abstract = {The exponential growth of the Internet during the last two decades has enabled the development of a wide variety of protocols and algorithms for efficient transfer of information. As most of the current Internet is based on the Internet Protocol (IP), packet delivery is "best effort". Certain packets may be dropped, altered, reordered or delayed. When deploying a new protocol or network solution, one needs to analyze and estimated the performance of that solution on the Internet. As the size and decentralized nature of the Internet renders such an analysis difficult, network emulators have been employed to create a simulated environment for packets running through the network. In this paper we present a flexible and extensible software network emulator that allows a great diversity of packet altering techniques. Our current implementation is running on Linux hosts only but its design allows easy porting to other platforms.},
